\begin_layout Section
Core Principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Game Master can override, suspend, ignore, or change in any way he wishes
 any rule in the game.
 The author is a big believer in the unknown, the mysterious, the things
 that should not be - not everything will be or play by the same rules the
 players use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The game is story-based - a Story Focus is created to provide conflict and
 tie the group together; Players choose Goals for their PCs, and the mechanics
 incent working toward them; and when the Goal is achieved, that PC's Story
 is over.
 Yes, that's correct - this RPG ends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The game tries to avoid rules that have no purpose other than to provide
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

game balance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (whatever that means).
 This means the rules are lighter and faster, but easily abused (if that's
 your thing).
 Anything not specifically forbidden is permitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The game is designed assuming a Combat-as-War play style.
 That means the rules make no attempt to make encounters fair, or balanced,
 or even survivable.
 That, in turn, means that the player characters will probably die.
 A lot.
 Hey, most worlds are dangerous places.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The game attempts to maximize in-scene immersion and minimize dissociated
 mechanics.
 That means the mechanics attempt, as much as feasible, to line up with
 what the characters would do or think.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Skills increase as they are used.
 Therefore, unlike most of FRPGs, there are no experience points (XP).
 Since there are also no classes, there are also no levels.
