\begin_layout Subsection*
Failing Skill Rolls - Fail Forward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Players can, at their option, choose to turn a skill roll failure into a
 partial success at the cost of a Consequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GM will ask which side of the tension they wish to resolve (if there
 is more than one choice) - or may simply tell them the outcome - and ask
 the Player to narrate how they do it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GM will then give the party a Consequence, to be repayed at the Story
 level at some time of the GM's choosing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Monsters have chased the party down a corridor ending in a locked door.
 The mechanic quickly whips out his lockpicks and kneels in front of the
 door.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GM tells the Player that this lock appears to have a difficulty equal
 to his rank.
 Under normal, unpressured circumstances, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pick this lock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be an automatic success, but with monsters closing in, the task becomes
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pick the lock before the monsters arrive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The additional time pressure also makes the task one step harder.
 The player rolls against the Skill Rank Table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A success roll would mean the lock is picked before the monsters arrive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A failed roll would mean the lock is not picked, and the monsters arrive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the player fails the roll, he may choose to Fail Forward for partial
 success - in this case, the lock is successfully picked after the monsters
 arrive, and the party gains a Consequence which the GM will call in later.
 Perhaps in this case, the monsters got a good look at the Characters and
 security and patrols are increased; or perhaps some equipment or important
 items is dropped; or the monsters choose to track the Characters and arrive
 again at an inopportune moment.
\end_layout

