\begin_layout Subsection*
Catalysts and Inhibitors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Catalysts and inhibitors are similar to reagents, except that they are not
 consumed during casting.
 Catalysts add spell points, inhibitors subtract points.
 The proper manner to utilize these must be learned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Rituals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rituals can accumulate points at say 1/hr or 1/day - spell(ish) specific(ish).
 Must be learned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rituals are long, complicated affairs that create a huge power reserve for
 use in implementing truly awe-inspiring effects.
 They are, for better or worse, rare in the extreme and poorly understood,
 even compared to normal magic.
 They usually require expensive, potent, or unique items, extensive planning
 and coordination, special environments, even multiple wizards, and are
 sensitive to mistakes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Enhancers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The knowledge of how, exactly, to use magical enhancers is not universal,
 although the existence of many such enhancers is common knowledge.
 Specific application requires study and practice, usually obtained via
 schools or teachers.
 The GM may grant a spell point, at his discretion, for any enhancer that
 the player invokes for a particular spell.
 He may also feel free to add, delete, or modify any of these to fit his
 setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Magical Laws:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Association - Commonality controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Similarity - Look-alikes are alike
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Attraction - Like attracts like, (or, Opposites attract)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Contagion - Once together, always together
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Synchronicity - Simultaneous occurrence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Law of Names - True Names give power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Natural Phenomena
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Natural places, items, or times that can enhance casting (or otherwise affect
 them...).
 Items here are beyond simple, generic reagents, and are unique in some
 additional sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ley lines - provide spell points environmentally, as well as a conduit for
 channeling power.
 There are stories of special place at the junction of multiple lines, and
 there are rumors of special junctions that act as spell point multipliers
 ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Moon/planet/astrological phases - provide spell points for the duration,
 or perhaps only at a specific time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Certain minerals or substances; flora, or pieces thereof; fauna, or particular
 parts, organs, or excretions thereof - see Reagents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Metamagic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Metamagic means spells dealing with manipulating magic itself.
 Some examples would be powering spells without spell points, or using natural
 power sources such as ley lines.
 Metamagic spells can even operate on other metamagic spells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These skills are typically 
\shape italic
not
\shape default
 taught in normal Wizard Schools, depending on setting, of course.
 The GM may decide how they may be acquired, or if they can be acquired
 at all.
 Examples might include in a long-lost library, from an ancient Wizard,
 a special school, an invitation-only order, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Open Channel: Allows a Wizard to establish an open channel to an power source
 for use in reducing the number of points needed for subsequent spells.
 In essence it turns a power source into a continuous, generic reagent.
 Spell points provided depend on the strength of the source, and can either
 be continuous or one-shot.
 Costs 1 spell point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Trigger: Allows a Wizard to cast a subsequent spell, and specify any set
 of conditions, which, when met, will release the spell.
 Costs 4 spell points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Delay: A simplified form of Trigger, simply delays a certain amount of time
 between the completion of casting and when the spell goes into effect.
 Costs 2 spell points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fork: Allows a Wizard to cast two subsequent spells, both of which will
 be released simultaneously.
 Almost always used with Trigger.
 Costs 2 spell points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chain: A specialized form of Trigger, allows a Wizard to attach a subsequently
 cast spell to a previously cast spell held in a Trigger or Fork.
 Costs 2 spell points.
 The second spell is released when the prior spell collapses (finishes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Hanging spells
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wizards can spend extra points to prepare spells for casting later on.
 Doing so alleviates the Will cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Resistance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certain places, items, or objects can function as natural inhibitors, in
 and of themselves, and / or by projecting such resistance.
 Such resistors effectively ignore spell points sourced from specifically
 resisted - that is, spells that would normally succeed will instead fail
 if removing the resisted points leaves insufficient power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mages hoping to overcome this resistance will likely need to research the
 target, potentialy special rituals, and almost certainly acquire specific
 components
\end_layout

