\begin_layout Standard
The Politics skill covers an PC's ability to non-violently persuade (that
 is, anything short of physical force) another party to do something.
 A PC has only one Politics Skill.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GM will set a difficulty before rolling, and rolls usually cannot be
 retried until circumstances change.
 Difficulty settings should be set considering any relevant items, especially
 any (known) Member, Relationship, or Connections ranks that might apply.
 Each of these is sufficient to modify the roll by one rank.
 Examples might be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Known Connections to a group significant to this action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Member of an Organization that will be interested in the outcome
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Relationship to a high political official.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before rolling, either party may 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sweeten the deal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by adding additional enticements.
 Significant sweeteners will modify the difficulty roll (for or against).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that after applying all applicable modifiers it is very possible that
 the roll is an automatic success or failure due to the resulting rank differenc
es.
 It is this fact that should encourage players to role play situations more
 deeply.
