\begin_layout Subsection*
Agora
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agora is the god of commerce.
 There are those outside the priesthood who believe Agora also stands for
 honesty in transactions; the priesthood is perfectly happy to allow them
 to continue believing that.
 Priests of Agora understand that while being honest is usually good business,
 it's not integral, merely practical, and not an absolute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Priests of Agora control the unions and guilds in all major cities,
 and have extensive relationships with most powers and organizations.
 When using this network, their Connections Rank is treated as two ranks
 higher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Priests of Agora are expected to tithe 10% of all their income to The Organizati
on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ironically, the leaders of the Thieves Guilds tend to be priests of Agora,
 rather than Khrusos - it's better for business.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Organization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Organization is the common name for the church of Agora.
 All priests of Agora are expected to belong to The Organization.
 Ties are very, very long and very, very deep - the group looks out for
 itself, and its own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Khrusos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Khrusos of the god of thievery and deceit.
 Priests of Khrusos exist to relieve others of their belongings, and are
 believed to be quite rare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Priests of Khrusos cannot be publicly so - no urban society will tolerate
 so obvious a lawbreaker.
 Thus they cannot have followers, and from hard-won experience almost never
 reveal themselves as such, even to their friends.
 They nevertheless often run a crew in a large urban setting.
 Such crews are often highly profitable, but short-lived, as they draw the
 attention of the authorities - the hands of Khrusos just can't seem to
 resist, even if it means having to go to ground for an extended period.
 Priests often specialize in one area of thievery - for instance, lower
